            <section class="mb-5">
                <p>
                    Even in the age of AI, reading comprehension remains an important human skill. Truly
                    understanding a text is about more than recognising words or pulling out facts; it requires
                    making sense of ideas, drawing inferences, following arguments, and noticing when something
                    does not quite add up (Kintsch, 1998; Perfetti &amp; Stafura, 2014). These abilities support
                    learning and critical thinking in every domain, and they are especially important when
                    engaging with AI-generated content, which still requires human judgement to interpret and
                    evaluate.
                </p>
                <p>
                    At the same time, reading comprehension may be especially vulnerable as AI tools increasingly
                    summarise, explain, and answer for us. When machines do more of the interpreting, we spend
                    less time practising the effortful work of deep reading. Over time, this is likely to weaken
                    our ability to follow complex texts or retain what we have read. The good news is that
                    comprehension is highly trainable: research shows that active practice &mdash; such as
                    answering targeted questions and reflecting on meaning &mdash; can significantly improve
                    understanding (National Reading Panel, 2000; McNamara, 2007). Well-designed multiple-choice
                    exercises help make this practice easy and effective.
                </p>
                <p>
                    These exercises are not designed to trick you, and they should not feel excessively difficult
                    for someone who actively engages their mind. The goal is less about finding a single
                    &ldquo;correct&rdquo; answer and more about encouraging careful reading, reflection, and
                    mental engagement. By thoughtfully considering the passages and answer choices, you are
                    exercising your comprehension skills and keeping your cognitive faculties sharp.
                </p>
            </section>

